SUMMARIZER="A">  

Pro- and anti- forces in the battle over the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) displayed their respective strengths this
week. President Clinton and former Presidents Bush, Carter and Ford
all endorsed NAFTA. Opponents interrupted a House hearing to unfurl an
anti-NAFTA banner and succeeded in getting extensive free TV
coverage. Meanwhile polls showed growing public opposition to the
trade pact with 36% of those polled opposed and 25% in favor.  A
Greenpeace release claimed that the agreement threatens two decades of
work on environmental protection, but Vice President Gore and several
established environmental leaders praised the environmental safeguards
negotiated in NAFTA's side pact.</SUM>

