SUMMARIZER="A">  

With the November 17 House vote on the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) fast approaching, the Clinton administration's
campaign for the pact has shifted into high gear. The White House will
soon announce support for a North American Development Bank to fund
projects in communities hit by job losses resulting from NAFTA. This
is expected to garner at least eight votes from Hispanic
congressmen. State by state, undecided congressmen are being invited
to the White House where the "war room" counts 110 Republicans in
favor, 65-75 Democrats in favor and 20-30 leaning in favor with 218
needed for passage.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-10911"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="A">  

As both sides feverishly jockey to gain the few votes needed to pass
or reject the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), strange
political alliances have been formed. With about 120 Republicans lined
up in favor, President Clinton needs at most 40% of his fellow
Democrats to pass the measure. While the administration has counted on
the "side agreements," covering Mexican environmental and labor laws
and guarding against import "surges" to win over those undecided on
the issue, these safeguards have not convinced labor and prominent
Democrats in Congress are leading the opposition while the radical
right wing supports the President.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
