SUMMARIZER="A">  

The battle over the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)
shifted to the Congressional districts this Veterans' Day weekend as
members sampled public opinion at home. Pro-NAFTA forces exulted over
Vice President Gore's debate victory over Ross Perot hoping it would
be decisive in the House vote next Wednesday. One poll of debate
watchers showed that support of NAFTA had shot up from 34% before the
debate to 57% after it. Meanwhile, anti-NAFTA leaders claimed 219
votes pledged against the pact (a small margin against switches) and
said the battle would be won or lost in the congressmen's home
districts.</SUM>


<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-8748"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="A">  

Investors believe the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) will
be good for the US economy. The superior products and industrial
productivity rates of the US will give it the greatest economic
benefits. But rejection of NAFTA might lead to more protectionism,
higher inflation and slower world economic growth.  Anti-NAFTA forces
fear that opening up trade with Mexico will lead to a migration of
American jobs south to Mexico's lower wages. Al Gore clearly bested
Ross Perot in the debate on Tuesday apparently winning over more
Americans to NAFTA, but it is clear that the vote Wednesday in
Congress will be close.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
